      "decision": "P0: Split shared Order/Courier database into separate instances",
      "gains": "Independent deployability, independent scaling, schema migration freedom, elimination of cross-service deadlock and connection pool contention",
      "sacrifices": "Temporary data synchronization complexity during migration, eventual consistency where today there is strong consistency, engineering effort for data migration",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Keep shared DB but enforce strict schema ownership via database-level permissions (lower effort but doesn't solve migration coupling)", "Use database views as a contract layer between the two services (medium effort, still couples at DB level)"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "P1: Replace synchronous Notification calls with async message queue",
      "gains": "Eliminates single point of failure, decouples deployment timelines, enables retry/dead-letter, improves latency for calling services",
      "sacrifices": "Added infrastructure (message broker), eventual delivery instead of immediate confirmation, need for idempotency in Notification Service",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Circuit breaker on synchronous calls (reduces blast radius but doesn't fix coupling)", "Sidecar proxy with async relay (complex, operational burden)"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "P2: Decompose Customer /everything endpoint into targeted endpoints",
      "gains": "Reduced payload size, better cacheability, ability to evolve sub-resources independently, improved security (principle of least privilege)",
      "sacrifices": "More endpoints to maintain, consumers must update integrations, potential N+1 if consumers need multiple sub-resources",
      "alternatives_considered": ["GraphQL for Customer Service (flexible but adds complexity and a new paradigm)", "Keep /everything but add sparse fieldsets via query params (band-aid, doesn't fix coupling)"]
    },
